// Researched content for caribbean-small. Written per property.
module.exports = {
  'cocobay-resort': {
    activities: `Cocobay's cottages climb a hillside above the southwest coast near Jolly Harbour, and the pace here is deliberately unplugged — no TVs, no phones in rooms, just a private balcony and sea views. Guests spend days on two small beach coves, snorkeling the reef just offshore, doing yoga on an open-air deck, and using the spa and gym. Antigua's broader sailing and snorkeling scene is close by via Jolly Harbour marina, and Shirley Heights and English Harbour's Nelson's Dockyard make for a good half-day trip east.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Cocobay sits above the coast in Bolans, about 20 minutes from V.C. Bird International Airport, and is built as an adults-only escape rather than a full-service resort — expect all-inclusive dining and drinks but a quieter, cottage-based footprint rather than towers and multiple pools. Location and service score especially well, the pool is modest by comparison, and the no-TV concept genuinely shapes the stay: it suits couples wanting a digital break more than anyone chasing nightlife. Antigua's driest, calmest weather runs January through April; the island sits south of the main hurricane belt but should still be watched August through October.`,
  },
  'blue-waters-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Blue Waters occupies its own peninsula north of St. John's, with two coves of beach, a dedicated adult pool alongside the family pool, and a full kids' club to keep the resort genuinely family-friendly. Watersports rentals, snorkeling off the point, tennis courts, and a spa round out the on-site list. Off property, St. John's cruise port and its duty-free shopping are a short drive, as is English Harbour and Nelson's Dockyard to the south, along with Antigua's catamaran day-sail circuit.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Blue Waters sits on a private peninsula a short drive from V.C. Bird International Airport and from the capital, St. John's, making it one of the more convenient family resorts on the island. It's all-inclusive with a buffet plus room service, and rooms sized for five or more make it workable for larger families. Cleanliness and location are its strongest marks; the beach and pool are decent rather than exceptional, so expect a solid, well-run resort rather than a showpiece one. Antigua's driest months run January to April, and the island sits outside the worst of the hurricane belt.`,
  },
  'stonefield-villa-resort': {
    activities: `Stonefield's villas are scattered across a former cocoa and coconut plantation on the hillside below Petit Piton, and the estate itself is the main attraction — nature trails through the grounds, a working cocoa exhibit, yoga classes on an open pavilion, and a spa built into the property. There's a pool with Piton views, but no swimmable beach on site; guests taxi or shuttle to Sugar Beach or Anse Chastanet for sand and snorkeling, or arrange diving and volcano tours into Soufrière town.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Stonefield sits in the hills above Soufrière, on Saint Lucia's dramatic southwest coast beneath the twin Pitons, reached via George F.L. Charles Airport in Castries (roughly ninety minutes by road) or the closer Hewanorra Airport in Vieux Fort. This is a villa-cottage property, not a beachfront resort — its beach score is among the lowest in our database because there simply isn't one on site, so book it for the setting, privacy, and hiking rather than for swimming. Rooms, service, and location otherwise score very highly. It's adults-friendly (17+) rather than strictly couples-only. December through April is Saint Lucia's driest stretch, though the volcanic south stays green and often cloudier than the north.`,
  },
  'rabot-hotel': {
    activities: `Rabot sits on a working cacao estate in the hills above Soufrière, and its identity is built around chocolate — cocoa-to-bar tours of the plantation, spa treatments using estate-grown cacao, and a restaurant serving cacao-infused dishes alongside estate produce. Guests hike the plantation trails, take in views of Petit Piton, and use the pool on site; there's no beach here, so it's a short taxi to Sugar Beach or Anse Chastanet for swimming, snorkeling, or diving trips out of Soufrière.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Rabot occupies a cacao plantation in the hills above Soufrière on Saint Lucia's volcanic southwest coast, most practically reached via Hewanorra Airport in Vieux Fort or the longer drive from George F.L. Charles in Castries. It's a small, adults-only, no-TV property built around its chocolate-estate concept rather than a conventional beach resort — the beach score is the lowest in our data because there is none on site. Rooms, cleanliness, and service all score exceptionally well, so this suits couples after a quiet, design-forward stay with a real sense of place rather than swim-up bars. December through April is the dry season; expect a cooler, greener, more cloud-prone climate than Saint Lucia's north.`,
  },
  'ti-kaye-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Ti Kaye's cottages sit on a bluff above Anse Cochon, connected to the beach cove below by a long stairway, and diving is the main draw — the bay has an easy reef and a sunken wreck right offshore, both reachable through the on-site dive center. Snorkeling gear, an infinity pool, spa treatments, and hiking trails round out the property, and Soufrière's volcano, sulphur springs, and botanical gardens are a short drive south for a change of pace.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Ti Kaye sits on Anse Cochon, a cove on Saint Lucia's west coast between Castries and Soufrière, most easily reached via George F.L. Charles Airport. It's all-inclusive and adults-oriented, built into a hillside so the beach requires a stairway rather than a flat walk — worth knowing if mobility is a concern. Rooms, service, and cleanliness all score strongly, and the diving and snorkeling right off the beach are a genuine highlight rather than a bolt-on. It suits couples looking for a quieter, more intimate property over a big all-inclusive complex. December through April is the driest window on this lush, volcanic island.`,
  },
  'bel-jou-hotel': {
    activities: `Bel Jou is a small hillside hotel above Castries harbour, and its own facilities are simple — a pool, a restaurant serving a buffet, occasional evening entertainment, and a spa — rather than the multi-pool, multi-restaurant scale of Saint Lucia's bigger resorts. There's no real beach on site, so most days involve a taxi to Rodney Bay or Vigie Beach for swimming, or day trips south to Soufrière's Pitons, sulphur springs, and botanical gardens.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Bel Jou sits above Castries, Saint Lucia's capital, close to George F.L. Charles Airport, which makes arrival and departure easy even if the hotel itself isn't beachfront — its beach score is one of the lowest in our data. Value and service stand out, and cleanliness is strong, but this is a modest, no-frills hotel rather than a resort, better suited to travelers prioritizing price and location over pools, dining variety, or sand. It works for couples wanting a base near the capital rather than a resort compound. December through April brings Saint Lucia's driest, sunniest weather.`,
  },
  'avila-beach-hotel': {
    activities: `Avila Beach Hotel occupies a former governor's residence on Willemstad's waterfront, and its own small beach and pier sit right on site, alongside a pool, dive shop, and watersports rentals for snorkeling the calm reefs just offshore. The hotel's art collection and colonial architecture are worth a wander in their own right. Willemstad's UNESCO-listed Handelskade waterfront, the floating market, and the Queen Emma pontoon bridge are all a short walk or taxi away, and Curaçao's easy shore diving is a short boat ride further out.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Avila Beach Hotel sits directly in Willemstad, a few minutes from Curaçao International (Hato) Airport, giving it a city-and-beach combination rather than a remote resort setting. It's all-inclusive with a buffet, and the family-friendly layout works for a range of ages, though the beach itself is modest by Caribbean standards — Curaçao's coastline runs more to coves and reef than long stretches of sand, and the ratings reflect that honestly. Location, cleanliness, and service are its strengths. Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and warm nearly year-round, so there's no strong high/low season pointer beyond avoiding the busiest holiday weeks.`,
  },
  'carlisle-bay-antigua': {
    activities: `Carlisle Bay sits on its own sheltered bay on Antigua's south coast, with a genuine swimming beach, a full watersports program including windsurfing and snorkeling, a well-regarded tennis setup, and a kids' club that makes this a serious family option rather than an adults-leaning resort with children tacked on. A spa, gym, and yoga classes cover the quieter side. English Harbour and Nelson's Dockyard are a short drive away for a half-day of colonial history and harbor views.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Carlisle Bay occupies a protected cove in Saint Mary's parish on Antigua's south coast, about 30-40 minutes from V.C. Bird International Airport. It's all-inclusive with a buffet and a genuinely strong family setup — rooms, cleanliness, and service all rate highly, and the beach here is one of the better ones in our database rather than an afterthought. The resort suits families wanting a quieter bay setting over the busier north-coast strip. Antigua's driest, most reliable weather runs January through April, with the hurricane season peaking August through October, though the island sees less rain than its neighbors even then.`,
  },
  'windjammer-landing-resort-and-residences': {
    activities: `Windjammer Landing's villas cascade down a hillside above Labrelotte Bay, linked by a series of pools that step toward the beach below. It's built for families, with both a kids' club and a teen club, tennis, horseback riding, watersports rentals, and snorkeling off the beach; a spa and yoga classes cover the adults. Rodney Bay's restaurants and marina are a short drive north, and Saint Lucia's rainforest zip-lining and the Soufrière volcano circuit make for a good day trip south.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Windjammer Landing sits above Labrelotte Bay on Saint Lucia's northwest coast, about 15-20 minutes from George F.L. Charles Airport in Castries. It's all-inclusive with a buffet, built as villas rather than a single tower, which means some walking (or a shuttle) between rooms, pools, and the beach — worth knowing for anyone with mobility concerns. Cleanliness and service score well, and the beach is decent rather than a standout. Its dual kids'/teen club setup makes it a genuine family choice rather than a couples resort. December through April is Saint Lucia's driest window, and the island stays green year-round thanks to its volcanic terrain.`,
  },
  'escape-at-nonsuch-bay-antigua': {
    activities: `Escape at Nonsuch Bay sits on a sheltered bay on Antigua's east coast, known locally for steady wind that makes it a good spot for sailing and windsurfing, alongside snorkeling on the reef just offshore and a spa for quieter days. It's a small, low-key property rather than a big resort complex, so days tend toward the beach and bay rather than a long amenities list. Half Moon Bay and the Stingray City excursion are both a reasonably short drive away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Escape at Nonsuch Bay sits on Antigua's less-developed east coast, about 30-40 minutes from V.C. Bird International Airport. It's all-inclusive and adults-only, and its rooms are the standout in our data — among among the highest-rated in our database — while the beach itself is modest rather than a wide stretch of sand, so it's better suited to travelers prioritizing quiet and comfort over a classic beach-resort setup. Cleanliness and value both score well too. It suits couples wanting a genuinely small, low-key property. January through April is Antigua's driest period, with hurricane season risk (generally modest for Antigua) peaking August through October.`,
  },
  'coconut-bay-beach-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Coconut Bay is one of Saint Lucia's largest resorts, split into family and adults-only sections, with a full waterpark (including slides and a lazy river), a kids' and teen club, tennis, horseback riding, and a busy evening entertainment schedule including a nightclub. The beach faces the Atlantic side of the island, so it's breezier and better for a walk than for calm swimming; snorkeling, diving, and windsurfing are all offered through the resort's watersports program.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Coconut Bay sits in Vieux Fort on Saint Lucia's southern tip, minutes from Hewanorra International Airport, which makes it the most convenient large resort on the island for arrival. It's all-inclusive with a buffet and a genuinely broad amenity list, geared heavily toward families with its waterpark and kids'/teen clubs, though an adults-only section exists within the property. The beach here is exposed to Atlantic wind and swell rather than calm Caribbean water, which shows up in its rating; value and pool facilities are stronger points. December through April is the driest season, and the south of the island tends to be windier than the sheltered west coast.`,
  },
  'renaissance-wind-creek-aruba-resort': {
    activities: `Renaissance Wind Creek Aruba sits in downtown Oranjestad, and its private Renaissance Island is the headline feature — a short ferry ride to two beaches, including an adults-only one where resident flamingos wander the shoreline. On the main property there's a casino, a marina, a spa, and a full dive and watersports program, plus an adult pool. Oranjestad's shopping and restaurants are steps away, and it's an easy base for exploring Arikok National Park and Aruba's windsurfing beaches further north.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This resort sits in the middle of Oranjestad, a few minutes from Aruba's Reina Beatrix Airport, giving it a city location rather than a beach strip — its actual sand access is via the private ferry to Renaissance Island rather than a beach out front. It's all-inclusive with a buffet, casino, and strong family amenities including a kids' club. Location and beach (via the island) both score well; the on-site pool is more middling. It suits families and casino-minded travelers who don't mind a short boat ride for their beach day. Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and warm nearly all year.`,
  },
  'sandals-grande-st-lucian': {
    activities: `Sandals Grande St Lucian sits on a peninsula near Pigeon Island, with beach frontage on both the calm Caribbean side and the breezier Atlantic side, so there's a choice of which to swim from. The resort runs an included scuba program for certified divers, a swim-up bar, tennis, and nightly entertainment across several restaurants. Rodney Bay's marina, restaurants, and nightlife are a short walk away, and Pigeon Island National Landmark, with its old fort and hiking trails, sits right next door.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `This is a couples-only resort on a peninsula in Gros Islet, at the north end of Saint Lucia, about 25 minutes from George F.L. Charles Airport in Castries. It's fully all-inclusive with multiple restaurants and included diving for certified guests, and the beach, location, and cleanliness all score strongly — a genuinely well-rounded property by Sandals' usual standard. It's built for couples rather than families, with no children on site. Being adjacent to Rodney Bay means nightlife and dining options beyond the resort are easy to reach. December through April is Saint Lucia's dry season and the most reliable time to visit.`,
  },
  'sandals-royal-curacao': {
    activities: `Sandals Royal Curaçao is best known for its over-the-water villas built out over a lagoon, a first for a Sandals property and one of the few in the Caribbean. Beyond that, the resort runs a large pool complex with swim-up bar, an included scuba program for certified divers, and a full nightly entertainment schedule across its restaurants. The beach is modest, typical of Curaçao's coastline, so most swimming happens in the resort's pools or on dive and snorkel trips to the island's reefs.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sandals Royal Curaçao opened in the Nieuwpoort area near Willemstad in 2023, a short drive from Curaçao International (Hato) Airport. It's a couples-only, fully all-inclusive resort, and its rooms, pools, and cleanliness all rate exceptionally well — among among among the strongest scores in our database. The trade-off is the beach: Curaçao's natural coastline runs to small coves rather than long sand stretches, so plan on the pool or day trips to Klein Curaçao for a classic beach day. This suits couples looking for a design-forward, newer property over a beach-first one. Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt and is reliably dry and warm most of the year.`,
  },
  'sandals-halcyon-beach': {
    activities: `Sandals Halcyon Beach sits on Choc Bay just north of Castries, with a swim-up bar, tennis courts, and an included scuba program for certified divers among its on-site draws. It's the more low-key of Saint Lucia's Sandals properties, with a straightforward beach-and-pool routine rather than a sprawling amenity list. Rodney Bay's restaurants and marina are a short drive north, and Castries itself, along with the cruise port and market, is close enough for an easy afternoon out.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sandals Halcyon Beach sits on Choc Bay, a few minutes from George F.L. Charles Airport in Castries, making it one of the more convenient Sandals properties to reach on the island. It's couples-only and all-inclusive, with strong service and cleanliness scores; the beach and pool are solid without being the island's best. It's a good entry point to the Sandals brand in Saint Lucia for travelers who want proximity to the capital over a more remote setting like Rodney Bay or Soufrière. December through April is the driest, most dependable season to visit.`,
  },
  'tamarijn-aruba': {
    activities: `Tamarijn sits directly on Druif Beach and shares grounds and a dine-around privilege with its sister property, Divi Aruba, next door, so guests effectively get two resorts' worth of restaurants and pools. On-site there's tennis, bicycle rentals, windsurfing and snorkeling off the beach, a kids' club, and nightly entertainment. Aruba's calm, wide beaches make this an easy, low-effort base, and Oranjestad's shops and casinos are a short drive north.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Tamarijn is a low-rise, casual family resort on Druif Beach, about 10 minutes from Reina Beatrix Airport. It's all-inclusive with a buffet, and its beach is one of the better-rated in our database, wide and calm in typical Aruba fashion. Food and atmosphere score more modestly, reflecting its straightforward, value-oriented positioning rather than a luxury one — it suits families wanting reliable beach time over an elevated dining scene. Being paired with Divi Aruba next door adds restaurant variety without leaving the property. Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and sunny nearly year-round, so timing is more about crowds and price than weather.`,
  },
  'sandals-regency-la-toc': {
    activities: `Sandals Regency La Toc sits on its own bay just outside Castries, and its nine-hole golf course is the standout on-site feature among Saint Lucia's Sandals properties, alongside tennis, a swim-up bar, and an included scuba program for certified divers. The grounds are large enough to feel spread out rather than compact. Castries and its cruise port, market, and Morne Fortune viewpoint are a short drive away, and Rodney Bay's nightlife is reachable within twenty minutes or so.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sandals Regency La Toc sits on La Toc Bay just outside Castries, close to George F.L. Charles Airport. It's a couples-only, all-inclusive resort with strong location and cleanliness scores; the on-site golf course is a genuine differentiator from its sister Sandals properties on the island. The beach is decent rather than exceptional, typical of the sheltered bays around Castries. It suits couples who want golf alongside the standard Sandals routine of included diving, multiple restaurants, and nightly entertainment. December through April is Saint Lucia's dry season, the most reliable stretch for beach and golf days alike.`,
  },
  'coco-palm': {
    activities: `Coco Palm is built around a lagoon-style pool at the center of a village-like courtyard in Rodney Bay, with the resort's restaurant and bar life centered there rather than on a private beach. Reduit Beach, one of Saint Lucia's best, is a short walk away for swimming and watersports. Rodney Bay's marina, restaurants, and nightlife are all within walking distance too, making this more of a walkable-town base than a self-contained resort.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Coco Palm sits in Rodney Bay village, about 20 minutes from George F.L. Charles Airport, and its location is the real selling point — restaurants, bars, and Reduit Beach are all walkable, even though the hotel itself has no beach on site (its beach score is among among the lowest in our database). Value scores highest of all its categories, reflecting a lower price point than beachfront resorts nearby. It suits travelers who want to walk to dinner and nightlife rather than stay fully on-property. December through April is Saint Lucia's driest season, best for exploring Rodney Bay on foot.`,
  },
  'bay-gardens-beach-resort': {
    activities: `Bay Gardens Beach Resort sits directly on Reduit Beach, widely considered one of Saint Lucia's best swimming beaches, and the resort leans into that with a kids' club, a water-feature pool, snorkeling and watersports rentals, and a spa for the adults. Rodney Bay's marina, restaurants, and nightlife are all within walking distance, and it's a convenient base for day trips south to the Pitons, Soufrière's drive-in volcano, and the botanical gardens at Diamond Falls.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Bay Gardens Beach Resort sits on Reduit Beach in Rodney Bay, about 20 minutes from George F.L. Charles Airport, part of a small, locally owned group of Bay Gardens properties in the same neighborhood. It's all-inclusive with a buffet, and its beachfront location is a genuine strength — the beach score here is solid, and cleanliness and service both rate well too. It suits families wanting a walkable village setting with restaurants and nightlife nearby rather than an isolated resort compound. December through April is Saint Lucia's dry season and the best time for beach days.`,
  },
  'the-verandah-antigua': {
    activities: `The Verandah's villas sit on a hillside above Dian Bay on Antigua's less-developed east coast, with a beach below, mini golf, tennis, and a full watersports program including snorkeling and fishing charters. It's part of the same small portfolio as Antigua's Hawksbill and Pineapple Beach Club resorts, so guests can typically use amenities across those nearby sister properties too. Half Moon Bay, one of Antigua's best beaches, and Devil's Bridge are both a short drive away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `The Verandah sits on Antigua's east coast in Saint Phillips parish, about 30-40 minutes from V.C. Bird International Airport — a quieter, less-developed part of the island than the north or west coast strips. It's all-inclusive and adults-friendly, with strong room and cleanliness scores; food and atmosphere are more middling, in keeping with its relaxed, low-key positioning rather than a lively resort scene. It suits couples wanting quiet beaches and hillside villas over nightlife. Antigua's driest, most reliable months run January through April, and the island is less exposed to hurricanes than islands further north.`,
  },
  'secrets-baby-beach-aruba': {
    activities: `Secrets Baby Beach sits directly on Baby Beach, a naturally sheltered, shallow lagoon on Aruba's southeast tip that's ranked among the calmest swimming spots on the island — good for snorkeling right off the sand. On site, the resort runs an unlimited-luxury dining program across several restaurants with no reservations required, a spa, and a gym, with a quieter, adults-only atmosphere than the busier Palm Beach strip further north. Charlie's Bar and San Nicolas's street art are a short walk into town.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Secrets Baby Beach Aruba is a newer AMResorts property on the island's southeast tip in San Nicolas, about 20-25 minutes from Reina Beatrix Airport, further from the main Palm Beach hotel strip. Its ratings are strong across the board — rooms, cleanliness, and sleep quality all rate among among the highest in our database — reflecting its position as one of Aruba's newer, higher-end all-inclusives. Baby Beach's calm, shallow water makes it a genuinely good swimming beach, unusual for a windier island otherwise known for surf and sailing conditions. It's adults-only and suits couples. Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and warm essentially year-round.`,
  },
  'divi-aruba': {
    activities: `Divi Aruba sits on Druif Beach and shares a dine-around arrangement with its sister property, Tamarijn, next door, giving guests access to both resorts' restaurants and pools. On site there's a casino, a kids' club, and the standard beach lineup of snorkeling and watersports rentals in Aruba's calm, clear water. Oranjestad's shops, restaurants, and nightlife are a short drive north, and the island's Arikok National Park is an easy half-day trip.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Divi Aruba sits on Druif Beach, about 10 minutes from Reina Beatrix Airport, and its beach is one of the better-rated features in our data — wide, calm, and typically Aruban. Food and atmosphere score more modestly, in line with its casual, value-driven positioning rather than an upscale one. It's a family resort with a casino and kids' club, and the dine-around link with neighboring Tamarijn adds restaurant variety. Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt and is reliably dry and sunny nearly year-round, so the main timing consideration is avoiding the busiest, priciest holiday weeks rather than weather.`,
  },
  'zoetry-marigot-bay-st-lucia': {
    activities: `Zoëtry Marigot Bay sits inside one of Saint Lucia's most photographed harbors, a narrow, palm-lined bay ringed by hills, and the setting itself is a big part of the appeal. On site there's an infinity pool, a swim-up bar, a spa, and fishing charters out of the marina; the beach is a small, imported strip rather than open sand, so most swimming happens in the pool or on boat trips out to the island's better beaches and reefs. Marigot Bay's restaurants and yacht traffic are steps away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Zoëtry Marigot Bay sits inside Marigot Bay on Saint Lucia's west coast, about 20 minutes from George F.L. Charles Airport. It's an AMResorts luxury property, all-inclusive, with food, atmosphere, and rooms all rating strongly — but the beach is genuinely small and partly man-made, one of the lower beach scores in our database, so it's a resort to book for the harbor setting and service rather than for classic wide-sand swimming. Room limits (max three per room) mark it as couples- and small-family-oriented rather than built for larger groups. December through April is Saint Lucia's dry season and the most reliable time to visit.`,
  },
  'sandals-grande-antigua-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Sandals Grande Antigua sits on Dickenson Bay, one of the island's best swim beaches, just outside St. John's. The resort runs an included scuba program for certified divers, a swim-up bar, tennis, a nightclub, and a full slate of restaurants for nightly entertainment. St. John's itself, with its cruise port, market, and duty-free shopping, is a short drive away, as is English Harbour and Nelson's Dockyard on the south coast for a half-day of colonial history.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sandals Grande Antigua sits on Dickenson Bay near St. John's, about 15 minutes from V.C. Bird International Airport, making it one of the most convenient Sandals properties on the island to reach. It's couples-only and fully all-inclusive, with a strong beach score reflecting Dickenson Bay's reputation as one of Antigua's best, plus solid cleanliness and location marks. Pool and atmosphere are more middling by comparison. It suits couples wanting proximity to St. John's and its shopping and dining over a more remote setting. January through April is Antigua's driest period, with hurricane risk (generally modest here) peaking August through October.`,
  },
  'hawksbill-resort-antigua': {
    activities: `Hawksbill spreads across four small beaches on a peninsula in Five Islands, including a clothing-optional cove that's one of the better-known features of an Antigua stay here. Snorkeling, hiking the peninsula's trails, and tennis fill the days, with the resort's own beaches doing most of the work rather than a large pool complex. St. John's and its cruise-port shopping are a short drive away, and English Harbour's dockyard makes for an easy day trip south.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hawksbill sits on a peninsula in Five Islands, about 15-20 minutes from V.C. Bird International Airport. It's an Elite Island Resorts property, all-inclusive, allowing guests 12 and up rather than being strictly adults-only. The beach score here is strong, helped by its four coves, including a clothing-optional one; the pool and general atmosphere score more modestly, reflecting a more casual, older-style resort than Antigua's newer luxury entries. It suits travelers prioritizing beach variety and a relaxed pace over polish. January through April is the driest window, and the island generally sees less hurricane exposure than islands further north.`,
  },
  'pineapple-beach-club-antigua': {
    activities: `Pineapple Beach Club sits on Long Bay, on Antigua's northeast coast, known for a shallow reef right off the beach that makes for some of the easiest snorkeling on the island. Tennis, evening entertainment, and a spa round out the on-site list, with the pace generally low-key rather than packed with programming. Devil's Bridge and Betty's Hope's sugar-plantation ruins are both a short drive away for a change of scene.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Pineapple Beach Club sits on Long Bay on Antigua's northeast coast, about 30-40 minutes from V.C. Bird International Airport. It's an Elite Island Resorts property allowing guests 16 and up, all-inclusive with a buffet, and its beach and location both rate solidly, largely thanks to Long Bay's calm, reef-protected water. Food, pool, and atmosphere are more modest, in keeping with its casual, unpretentious style rather than a polished luxury resort. It suits travelers who want easy snorkeling and a relaxed pace over nightlife or fine dining. January through April is Antigua's driest, most reliable season.`,
  },
  'divi-dutch-village-beach-resort': {
    activities: `Divi Dutch Village sits near Druif Beach in Aruba's Divi resort cluster, with suites built around kitchenettes for families who want some self-catering flexibility alongside the all-inclusive plan. Tennis, a kids' club, a swim-up bar, and the beach's usual snorkeling and watersports rentals fill the days, and guests here often have dine-around access to the neighboring Divi properties for more restaurant variety. Oranjestad's shops and casinos are a short drive away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Divi Dutch Village sits in the Divi resort cluster near Druif Beach, about 10 minutes from Reina Beatrix Airport. It's all-inclusive and family-oriented, with a solid beach score and reliable cleanliness and room marks; the pool and atmosphere are more middling, typical of a straightforward, value-focused resort rather than a design-forward one. Its Dutch-village-style architecture and kitchenette suites make it a practical pick for families wanting some flexibility. Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and sunny nearly all year, so timing mostly comes down to price and crowds rather than weather.`,
  },
  'barcelo-aruba': {
    activities: `Barceló Aruba sits on the Palm Beach high-rise strip, Aruba's busiest and most developed beach, with the usual lineup of pool time, beach loungers, and watersports rentals just steps from the hotel. Its location puts guests within walking distance of Palm Beach's restaurants, casinos, and nightlife, an easy contrast to quieter days spent snorkeling or simply on the sand, which rates among among among the best beaches in our database.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Barceló Aruba sits directly on Palm Beach, about 15 minutes from Reina Beatrix Airport, in the middle of Aruba's main hotel and casino strip. It's all-inclusive and family-oriented, with beach and location both rating very well, reflecting Palm Beach's reputation as one of the Caribbean's best all-around beaches. Food and atmosphere are more middling, typical of a large, straightforward resort rather than a boutique one. It suits families who want walkable restaurants and nightlife beyond the resort itself. Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and warm nearly year-round.`,
  },
  'divi-village-golf-and-beach-resort': {
    activities: `Divi Village sits alongside the Links at Divi Aruba golf course, making golf the clearest differentiator from its sister Divi properties nearby. Suites here lean toward condo-style, self-catering options, and guests typically have dine-around access to the beachfront Divi and Tamarijn resorts down the road for restaurant variety. The beach itself is a short walk or shuttle away rather than direct beachfront, with the usual Aruba lineup of snorkeling and watersports available there.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Divi Village sits near the golf course in the Divi resort cluster outside Oranjestad, about 10-15 minutes from Reina Beatrix Airport. It's all-inclusive and family-friendly, with solid, if unspectacular, scores across the board — this is a practical, value-oriented resort rather than a beachfront showpiece, and its beach access is via a short walk or shuttle rather than direct frontage. It suits golfers and families wanting condo-style flexibility over ocean-view rooms. Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt and is reliably dry and sunny nearly all year, so timing is mostly about avoiding peak-season pricing.`,
  },
  'sonesta-ocean-point-resort': {
    activities: `Sonesta Ocean Point is the adults-only, all-suite sister property to Sonesta Maho Beach Resort down the road, with its own infinity pools and a quieter, more upscale pace than the bigger family resort. Guests here typically have access to Maho's restaurants and casino via a short shuttle, alongside the calmer, more sheltered swimming at Pelican Key itself. Maho Beach's famous low-flying jet landings, Philipsburg's duty-free shopping, and Orient Beach on the French side are all easy day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sonesta Ocean Point sits on Pelican Key on the Dutch side of the island, on Sint Maarten, a short drive from Princess Juliana International Airport. It's adults-only and all-inclusive, and rooms and cleanliness both rate very highly — among among among the strongest scores in our database — while the beach here is smaller and calmer than the open stretches elsewhere on the island, which shows up modestly in that score. It suits couples wanting an upscale, quieter counterpart to the busier Maho strip nearby. Hurricane season (June to November, peaking August-October) is the main timing consideration on this island; December through April is driest and safest.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-palace-antillas': {
    activities: `Hotel Riu Palace Antillas sits on Palm Beach, Aruba's main hotel strip, with the beach itself doing most of the work — wide, calm, and rated among among the best in our database. On site there's a pool, a spa, a gym, and RIU's typical all-inclusive dining rotation; being adults-only keeps the atmosphere quieter than the family resorts along the same stretch. Palm Beach's casinos, restaurants, and nightlife are all within walking distance.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Riu Palace Antillas sits directly on Palm Beach, about 15 minutes from Reina Beatrix Airport, in the heart of Aruba's main resort strip. It's adults-only and all-inclusive, with beach and location both rating very well, in line with Palm Beach's reputation as one of the Caribbean's best. Food and atmosphere are more middling, typical of a large, formula-driven RIU property rather than a boutique one. It suits couples wanting walkable nightlife and dining alongside a top-tier beach. Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and sunny essentially year-round.`,
  },
  'divi-little-bay-beach-resort': {
    activities: `Divi Little Bay sits on its own cove, Little Bay, just outside Philipsburg, with a dive shop, snorkeling right off the beach, a kids' club, and a spa rounding out the property. Fort Amsterdam's ruins sit on the headland above the resort and make for an easy walk with harbor views. Philipsburg's cruise port, duty-free shopping, and restaurants are a short drive away, and Maho Beach's low-flying jets are a popular day-trip stop.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Divi Little Bay sits on Little Bay, just outside Philipsburg on the Dutch side of the island, a short drive from Princess Juliana International Airport. It's all-inclusive and family-friendly, with a decent beach and strong location score thanks to its proximity to Philipsburg. Food and atmosphere are more modest, typical of a straightforward, older-style resort rather than a newly renovated one. It suits families wanting easy access to Philipsburg's shopping and cruise-port energy. Hurricane season runs June through November, peaking August-October, so December through April is the more dependable window to visit.`,
  },
  'holiday-inn-resort-aruba': {
    activities: `Holiday Inn Resort Aruba sits on Palm Beach, with the beach itself the main event — wide, calm, and consistently well-rated. On-site amenities cover the family basics: pools, watersports rentals, and evening entertainment, with restaurants and casinos an easy walk along the strip beyond the resort. It's a straightforward base for beach days broken up by trips to Arikok National Park or the windsurfing beaches further north.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Holiday Inn Resort Aruba sits directly on Palm Beach, about 15 minutes from Reina Beatrix Airport, in the middle of Aruba's main hotel strip. It's all-inclusive and family-oriented, with the beach and location both scoring very well; food, pool, and atmosphere are more middling, in keeping with a familiar, dependable chain hotel rather than a luxury resort. It suits families who want a recognizable brand and walkable strip life over a boutique experience. Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and warm essentially year-round, so timing comes down to crowds and pricing more than weather.`,
  },
  'st-james-s-club-and-villas': {
    activities: `St. James's Club & Villas sits on its own peninsula in Mamora Bay on Antigua's south coast, with two beaches, a marina, and the standard watersports lineup of snorkeling and small-boat rentals. It's an Elite Island Resorts property, so amenities run toward tennis and a relaxed pool scene rather than a packed entertainment schedule. English Harbour and Nelson's Dockyard, with their Georgian naval-yard history, are a short drive away for a change of pace.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `St. James's Club sits on Mamora Bay near English Harbour on Antigua's south coast, about 30-40 minutes from V.C. Bird International Airport. It's all-inclusive and family-friendly, with solid, middle-of-the-road scores across most categories — a dependable rather than a standout property. Its peninsula setting and proximity to English Harbour's historic dockyard are its real draws. It suits families wanting a quieter south-coast base with easy access to Antigua's colonial-era sites. January through April is the driest period, and Antigua generally sees less hurricane exposure than islands to the north.`,
  },
  'hotel-riu-palace-aruba': {
    activities: `Hotel Riu Palace Aruba sits on Palm Beach, with the wide, calm sand doing most of the work for a beach day. On site, the resort runs pools, a gym, a spa, and RIU's all-inclusive dining rotation across its restaurants, with the strip's casinos and nightlife an easy walk beyond the property line. It's a straightforward base for families wanting beach time paired with easy access to Palm Beach's restaurants and shopping.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hotel Riu Palace Aruba sits directly on Palm Beach, about 15 minutes from Reina Beatrix Airport. It's all-inclusive and family-friendly, with beach and location both rating very highly, consistent with Palm Beach's reputation as one of the best all-around beaches in the Caribbean. Food, pool, and atmosphere score more modestly, in keeping with a large, formula-driven resort rather than a boutique one. It suits families who want a reliable, walkable strip location over a quieter or more design-forward property. Aruba sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and warm essentially year-round.`,
  },
  'oceans-at-divi-little-bay': {
    activities: `Oceans at Divi Little Bay is the newer, higher-end tower addition to the neighboring Divi Little Bay Beach Resort, and guests here typically share that property's beach, dive shop, and restaurants while getting more contemporary suites. Little Bay's cove offers easy snorkeling, and Fort Amsterdam's ruins sit on the headland just above for a short walk with harbor views. Philipsburg's shopping and cruise port, and Maho Beach's plane-spotting, are both short drives away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Oceans at Divi Little Bay sits alongside its sister property on Little Bay, just outside Philipsburg on the Dutch side of the island, a short drive from Princess Juliana International Airport. It's all-inclusive and family-friendly, with strong room and cleanliness scores reflecting its newer construction relative to Divi Little Bay next door. Food and atmosphere score more modestly. It suits families wanting updated rooms with easy access to Philipsburg's shopping and cruise-port energy. Hurricane season runs June through November, peaking August-October, so December through April is the more dependable window.`,
  },
  'secrets-st-lucia-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Secrets St. Lucia sits on a secluded cove on the island's Atlantic-facing east coast, a quieter, less-developed stretch than the busier west coast resorts. The all-inclusive routine here runs through several restaurants with no reservations required, a full-service spa, and a swimmable beach cove for snorkeling. It's a good base for exploring the less-touristed east coast, including nearby fishing villages, with Soufrière's volcano and Pitons a longer but doable day trip south.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Secrets St. Lucia sits on the island's east coast, a longer drive (roughly an hour) from George F.L. Charles Airport in Castries, in a quieter, more remote setting than the Rodney Bay or Soufrière resort clusters. It's adults-only and all-inclusive, with strong cleanliness, service, and sleep-quality scores; the beach is decent, a sheltered cove rather than a long stretch of sand. It suits couples wanting seclusion and quiet over nightlife and easy access to town. December through April is Saint Lucia's dry season, and the east coast tends to catch more Atlantic breeze than the sheltered west.`,
  },
  'bay-gardens-marina-haven-hotel': {
    activities: `Bay Gardens Marina Haven sits on Rodney Bay's marina rather than directly on the beach, so the setting leans toward boat traffic and waterfront dining rather than sand; Reduit Beach is a short walk away for swimming. The hotel is part of the same small, locally owned Bay Gardens group as the beachfront Bay Gardens Beach Resort nearby, and guests can typically use amenities across the group's properties. Rodney Bay's restaurants and nightlife are all within walking distance.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Bay Gardens Marina Haven sits on the Rodney Bay Marina, about 20 minutes from George F.L. Charles Airport, in a village-like setting with restaurants and shops close by rather than an isolated resort footprint. Its beach score is among among the lowest in our database, reflecting the fact that it's a marina-front hotel rather than a beach resort — Reduit Beach requires a short walk. Value is its clear strength, priced below the beachfront properties nearby. It suits travelers prioritizing budget and a walkable village setting over direct beach access. December through April is Saint Lucia's driest season.`,
  },
  'hideaway-at-royalton-saint-lucia': {
    activities: `Hideaway at Royalton is the adults-only section of the Royalton Saint Lucia complex in Cap Estate, near the island's northern tip, and guests here typically have access to the wider resort's restaurants and entertainment while keeping their own quieter pool and beach areas. Smugglers Cove Beach is right on site for swimming and snorkeling, and Pigeon Island National Landmark, with its old fort and walking trails, is a short drive away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Hideaway at Royalton sits in Cap Estate at Saint Lucia's northern tip, about 25-30 minutes from George F.L. Charles Airport. It's the adults-only wing of the larger Royalton Saint Lucia resort, all-inclusive, with solid room and cleanliness scores; the beach and pool are decent rather than exceptional. It suits couples wanting a quieter section within a bigger resort complex, with the option to use the main resort's wider dining and entertainment. December through April is Saint Lucia's dry season, the most dependable stretch for beach days at Smugglers Cove.`,
  },
  'royalton-saint-lucia': {
    activities: `Royalton Saint Lucia sits in Cap Estate at the island's northern tip, with Smugglers Cove Beach out front for swimming and snorkeling, plus a kids' club, pools, and nightly entertainment that make this the family-facing counterpart to the resort's adults-only Hideaway section next door. Pigeon Island National Landmark's old fort and trails are a short drive away, and Rodney Bay's restaurants and marina aren't far south.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Royalton Saint Lucia sits in Cap Estate, about 25-30 minutes from George F.L. Charles Airport, at the island's quieter northern tip. It's all-inclusive and family-oriented, with strong room and cleanliness scores and a decent, swimmable beach at Smugglers Cove. Food and atmosphere are more middling, typical of a large resort built for broad appeal rather than a boutique one. Families can also access the resort's adults-only Hideaway section's facilities in some cases, giving parents an evening-out option. December through April is Saint Lucia's dry season and the best window for beach time.`,
  },
  'mangrove-beach-corendon-curacao-resort': {
    activities: `Mangrove Beach Corendon sits along Mambo Beach Boulevard, Willemstad's beachfront strip of restaurants, bars, and shops, putting a lot of off-property dining and nightlife within walking distance. On-site there are pools, a spa, and the resort's own stretch of Mambo Beach for swimming and snorkeling. Willemstad's UNESCO-listed Handelskade waterfront and floating market are a short drive away, as is the Curaçao Sea Aquarium next door.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Mangrove Beach Corendon sits on Mambo Beach Boulevard in Willemstad, a short drive from Curaçao International (Hato) Airport, in one of the island's more built-up, restaurant-and-nightlife-dense stretches. It's all-inclusive and family-friendly, with generally middle-of-the-road scores across categories — a straightforward, value resort rather than a standout luxury one. Its boulevard location means plenty of off-property dining and shopping within an easy walk. Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and warm nearly year-round, so timing is mostly about avoiding the busiest, priciest weeks rather than weather.`,
  },
  'royalton-chic-antigua': {
    activities: `Royalton CHIC Antigua leans into a design-forward, adults-only version of the Royalton brand, with swim-up suites, a lively pool scene, and nightly entertainment as the core of the on-site routine. The beach here rates well among Antigua resorts. St. John's cruise port and shopping are a short drive away, and English Harbour's Nelson's Dockyard makes for an easy half-day trip to the island's colonial history.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Royalton CHIC Antigua sits in Cedar Grove on Antigua's west side, about 15-20 minutes from V.C. Bird International Airport. It's the adults-only, design-oriented sub-brand within the Royalton portfolio, all-inclusive, with a strong beach score and notably high marks for sleep quality. Value and service are more middling by comparison. It suits couples wanting a livelier, more stylish pool-and-nightlife scene than a quiet boutique property. January through April is Antigua's driest period, and the island generally sees less hurricane exposure than islands further north in the chain.`,
  },
  'the-rif-at-mangrove-beach-corendon-curacao': {
    activities: `The Rif is the newer tower addition alongside Mangrove Beach Corendon on Willemstad's Mambo Beach Boulevard, with a swim-up bar and its own pool scene set apart from the older resort next door, while sharing the same stretch of Mambo Beach and the boulevard's restaurants and shops. It's also one of the few pet-friendly all-inclusives in our database. Willemstad's Handelskade waterfront and floating market are a short drive away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `The Rif sits on Mambo Beach Boulevard in Willemstad, a short drive from Curaçao International (Hato) Airport, as the newer, higher-end companion tower to Mangrove Beach Corendon next door. Room limits (max three per room) suit couples and small families rather than large groups, and it's notably pet-friendly, unusual for an all-inclusive. Rooms and cleanliness score reasonably well; the beach is modest, in keeping with Curaçao's naturally rocky, cove-style coastline rather than long open sand. Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and warm nearly year-round.`,
  },
  'zoetry-curacao-resort-and-spa': {
    activities: `Zoëtry Curaçao is a boutique, adults-only property built around a small private beach cove and an adjacent golf course, with a spa, an infinity pool, and quiet grounds as the core of the stay rather than a big activity roster. The cove is modest by Caribbean standards — typical of Curaçao's naturally rocky coastline — so snorkeling and diving trips further along the island's reefs are a common add-on. Willemstad's Handelskade and floating market are a short drive away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Zoëtry Curaçao sits on the island's southeast coast near Willemstad, a short drive from Curaçao International (Hato) Airport. It's an adults-only, luxury boutique property, all-inclusive, with food, atmosphere, and rooms all rating strongly — its identity leans toward quiet, upscale relaxation rather than a big resort scene. The beach is the clear weak point, one of the lower scores in our database, consistent with Curaçao's cove-and-rock coastline rather than long open sand; plan to supplement with a boat trip to Klein Curaçao. Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and warm essentially year-round.`,
  },
  'kunuku-resort-curacao': {
    activities: `Kunuku Resort takes its name and style from Curaçao's traditional countryside kunuku estates, with low-rise bungalows set around pools rather than directly on the water — there's no real beach on site, so days typically involve a shuttle or drive to one of Willemstad's beach clubs or coves for swimming and snorkeling. The resort's own pools and casual restaurant cover most of the on-property time. Willemstad's Handelskade waterfront is a reasonably short drive away.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Kunuku Resort sits inland in Tera Kora, a short drive from both Willemstad and Curaçao International (Hato) Airport. It's all-inclusive and family-friendly, priced as one of the more budget-oriented options in our database, and that shows in its scores — solid but unspectacular across most categories, with the beach the clear weak point since the resort itself isn't beachfront. It suits travelers prioritizing value and a relaxed, countryside-style setting over direct beach access or polish. Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and warm nearly all year, so timing is mainly about price and crowds.`,
  },
  'the-soco-house': {
    activities: `The Soco House is a small, boutique-style property with a pool as its centerpiece rather than a large beach frontage — its beach score is modest, in keeping with a more intimate, town-adjacent hotel than a sprawling resort. Days here lean toward the pool, a restaurant and bar, and easy access to Rodney Bay's restaurants and marina nearby for dining out and boat trips. Reduit Beach is a short drive or walk for swimming.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `The Soco House sits near Rodney Bay on Saint Lucia's northwest coast, about 20 minutes from George F.L. Charles Airport. It's a small, boutique all-inclusive rather than a large resort complex, with strong cleanliness and location scores; the beach is a genuine weak point, one of the lower scores in our database, so plan on a short trip to Reduit Beach for swimming. It suits travelers wanting an intimate, low-key property with easy access to Rodney Bay's restaurants and nightlife. December through April is Saint Lucia's dry season and the best time for beach days nearby.`,
  },
  'sonesta-maho-beach-resort-casino-and-spa': {
    activities: `Sonesta Maho sits on Maho Beach, famous for the jets that pass just overhead on final approach to Princess Juliana Airport — a genuine spectacle best watched from the beach or the neighboring Sunset Bar. On site there's a casino, a spa, and the resort's own restaurants covering the all-inclusive routine, with sister property Sonesta Ocean Point's quieter pools a short shuttle away. Philipsburg's duty-free shopping and Orient Beach on the French side are both easy day trips.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sonesta Maho sits directly on Maho Beach, a short drive from Princess Juliana International Airport (whose runway is essentially the beach's backdrop). It's all-inclusive with a casino and family-friendly programming, and location scores well thanks to easy access to Philipsburg and the wider island; food and atmosphere are more middling, typical of a large, busy resort rather than a quiet one. It suits families and travelers drawn to the plane-watching novelty and casino nightlife over seclusion. Hurricane season runs June through November, peaking August-October, so December through April is the more dependable stretch.`,
  },
  'royalton-antigua': {
    activities: `Royalton Antigua sits on the west coast in Five Islands, with a beach that rates well among Antigua resorts, several pools, a spa, a kids' club, and nightly entertainment covering the family side. St. John's cruise port and duty-free shopping are a short drive away, and English Harbour's Nelson's Dockyard, with its Georgian naval history, makes for an easy half-day trip south. Sleep quality here is notably strong, one of the better marks in our database.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Royalton Antigua sits in Five Islands on the island's west coast, about 15-20 minutes from V.C. Bird International Airport. It's all-inclusive and family-oriented, with a solid beach and a notably strong sleep-quality score; value is the softer mark, suggesting it's priced at a premium relative to what it delivers compared with some neighbors. It suits families wanting a straightforward, full-service resort experience close to the airport and St. John's. January through April is Antigua's driest, most reliable season, and the island generally sees less hurricane exposure than islands further north in the chain.`,
  },
  'jolly-beach-antigua': {
    activities: `Jolly Beach Antigua fronts one of the island's longest stretches of sand, and the beach is genuinely the strongest reason to stay here — long, walkable, and good for a straightforward beach day. On-site amenities are basic rather than elaborate: pools, a buffet restaurant, and evening entertainment cover the essentials. It's a reasonable base for exploring Antigua's west coast, with Jolly Harbour's marina and restaurants nearby and Stingray City and catamaran day-sails easy to arrange.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Jolly Beach Antigua sits on Antigua's west coast, about 20 minutes from V.C. Bird International Airport. It's a large, budget-oriented, all-inclusive family resort, and its beach is a clear strength — among the better-rated in our database — while food, rooms, and atmosphere score noticeably lower, reflecting an older property competing mainly on price and beach access rather than polish. Room occupancy is capped at two per room, worth noting for families. It suits travelers prioritizing value and beach time over dining quality or updated rooms. January through April is Antigua's driest season.`,
  },
  'sunscape-curacao-resort-spa-and-casino': {
    activities: `Sunscape Curaçao sits near Willemstad's Mambo Beach and the Curaçao Sea Aquarium, and the resort's casino and family-oriented pool scene are the core of the on-site routine, alongside a kids' club and the usual buffet-driven all-inclusive dining. The Sea Aquarium and its dolphin encounters are right next door, and Willemstad's Handelskade waterfront, floating market, and Queen Emma pontoon bridge are all a short drive into town for an afternoon out.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Sunscape Curaçao sits near Willemstad, a short drive from Curaçao International (Hato) Airport, close to the Sea Aquarium and Mambo Beach boulevard. It's an AMResorts family brand positioned at a more accessible price point, all-inclusive with a casino, and its scores are middle-of-the-road across most categories rather than standout in any one — a dependable, value-oriented resort rather than a luxury pick. It suits families wanting a casino and easy access to Willemstad's attractions over a quiet, upscale stay. Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and warm nearly year-round.`,
  },
  'dreams-curacao-resort-spa-and-casino': {
    activities: `Dreams Curaçao sits in Piscadera Bay near Willemstad, with a casino, several pools, and a kids' club covering the family-resort basics, plus a beach cove for swimming and snorkeling that's modest by Caribbean standards. The Curaçao Sea Aquarium and Mambo Beach boulevard are a short drive away, as is Willemstad's Handelskade waterfront, for an afternoon of walking, shopping, and the floating vegetable market.`,
    whatYouNeedToKnow: `Dreams Curaçao sits in Piscadera Bay, a short drive from Willemstad and from Curaçao International (Hato) Airport. It's all-inclusive and family-oriented with a casino, but its overall rating is among the lowest in our database, and value scores low too — worth going in with tempered expectations on food and overall polish relative to price. Sleep quality is a genuine bright spot by comparison. It's a workable option for families wanting a casino and central location on a budget, more than a resort to book for its dining or overall finish. Curaçao sits outside the hurricane belt and stays dry and warm nearly all year.`,
  },
}
